<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akayev Sees Grounds for Stronger Ties With India </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Akayev Sees Grounds for Stronger Ties With India </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606165294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1516 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606165294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Askar Akayev believes that in the past two 
years firm foundations for developing friendly relations between 
Kyrgyzstan and India have been built. He said so in Bishkek on 
Monday [6 June], accepting credentials from India's Ambassador 
to Bishkek, Ramswaruh Mukherjee. 
  Akayev said he hopes that the visit to Bishkek by India's 
Foreign Minister, Salman Khurshid, will help to resolve many 
problems connected with bilateral agreements. 
  It will be a three-day visit. On Tuesday, the head of the 
Indian diplomatic service will join a session of the bilateral 
commission on economic cooperation. On Wednesday, he will 
confer with President Akayev and other Kyrgyz leaders. On 
Thursday, Salman Hurshid is expected to give a news conference. 
Friday morning he will leave for Dushanbe. 

</TEXT>

