<DATE1>  6 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   1994 Budget Amendments Still Under Review </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    1994 Budget Amendments Still Under Review </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606152794 Almaty Kazakh Radio Network in Kazakh 1400 GMT 
6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0606152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Almaty Kazakh Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Kazakh </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sergey Tereshchenko chaired a regular sitting of the 
Cabinet of Ministers today. The topic of discussion was the 
1994 state budget. Most discussions centered on the apparently 
insufficient proposals by departmental ministries with regard to 
cutting budget expenditures. 
  If these proposals are taken as a basis, not only will the 
expenditures not be cut; rather, the earlier envisaged deficit 
will increase threefold. The participants of the sitting 
expressed fair doubts that the income part of the budget, which 
had been confirmed earlier, was feasible. Many enterprises and 
even branches of industry are currently loss-generating, while 
credit turnover is extremely low. 
  A decision was made to petition for review by the Supreme 
Kenges the possibility of a gradual stage-by-stage increase of 
prices for bread and bakery products that currently are 
subsidized. The need for measures to protect the poorest 
segments of the population was also raised. 

</TEXT>

