<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Akayev on Expectations From NATO </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Akayev on Expectations From NATO </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606192394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1843 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606192394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In joining the NATO Partnership for Peace program, 
Kyrgyzstan hopes to receive assistance on the part of NATO 
within the scope of the consultations on national security. 
Kyrgyzstan also expects NATO to help it to work out a military 
doctrine. 
  Speaking at a press conference in Bishkek today, Kyrgyz 
President Askar Akayev commented on the results of his visit to 
NATO headquarters. He underlined that within the scope of this 
program NATO was ready to assist with drafting projects for 
conversion of the Kyrgyz military industry. The parties could 
also cooperate on environmental projects. 
  In particular, Bishkek wishes for NATO to provide practical 
aid to overcome natural disasters which are a regular occurrence 
in Kyrgyzstan. 
  Akayev pointed out that although Kyrgyzstan is a small 
state, 
the general situation in Central Asia and its interests in 
stability and security mean that it must have its own army. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

