<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Round-the-Clock Security Patrols Start </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Round-the-Clock Security Patrols Start </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706072994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0657 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706072994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Gridneva] </F>
  [Text] Dushanbe 7 June TASS -- Armed squads of the Tajik 
Security, Interior, and Defence Ministries, as well as of the 
Russian military contingent deployed in Dushanbe, today began to 
patrol the streets of the Tajik capital round-the-clock. These 
security measures were approved on Monday by the coordination 
council of Tajik law enforcement bodies, which met here under 
the chairmanship of First Vice-Speaker of the Tajik Supreme 
Soviet Abdulmadjid Dostiyev. The vice-speaker said that they 
were prompted by the current dangerous criminogenic situation in 
the city, which had, in fact, gone out of control in recent days. 
  As earlier reported, a wave of terroristic acts swept the 
Tajik capital this May. Their victims included prominent Tajik 
businessmen and journalists, as well as officers of the Russian 
military contingent and the national armed forces. 
  The patrol squads are vested with extensive rights, 
including 
the right to inspect all types of transport vehicles, check the 
documents of citizens, and confiscate unlawfully possessed 
weapons. The areas, where Russian servicemen and their families 
are housed, are being guarded with particular care. 
  The patrols are allowed to open fire in case of resistance 
or 
refusal to obey their orders. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

