<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Bank Halts Registration of New Commercial Banks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    National Bank Halts Registration of New Commercial Banks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0406165594 Tbilisi REZONANSI in Georgian 26-27 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU0406165594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi REZONANSI </F>
<F P=105>  Georgian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Kakha Beradze report: "The Registration of Commercial </F>
Banks Was Halted in Georgia on 25 May"] 
  [Text] As has been pointed out in the National Bank, there 
has been a more than sufficient increase in their number. As of 
24 May, the number of commercial banks that had been registered 
amounted to 210, of which 138 were set up during the last year 
and a half. 
  According to specialists, such an increase in the number of 
commercial banks has been due to the inflation of the coupon. 
The exchange rate of the coupon is increasing constantly 
whereas the minimum capital fund for newly created banks 
remains, as before, 500 million coupons. If, in January, this 
amount was equivalent to $3,000, it was worth $480 by mid-May. 
It is unrealistic to open an enterprise with this amount, yet 
it is wholly possible to open a commercial bank, which Georgian 
businessmen, moreover, are using to their advantage. It is 
precisely for this reason that commercial banks have sprung up 
like mushrooms; the National Bank has put a temporary halt to 
their further increase until new rates are established for the 
minimum capital fund. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

