<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Resigns Over KGB Allegations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Resigns Over KGB Allegations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606154394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1500 
GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0606154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Riga, 6 Jun -- Latvian Foreign Minister Georgs 
Andrejevs on Monday asked the government to accept his 
resignation. He also gave up his seat as a member of the Saeima 
today. His powers as a deputy were suspended by parliament at 
the end of April because the minister's name was discovered in a 
card index of agents of the former KGB. 
  At the same time, Andrejevs issued a statement in which he 
expresses the hope that his resignation will "help society and 
legislators realize the need to make changes to Latvia's laws." 
He believes that only a proven fact should serve as the reason 
for punishing or limiting the activity of an individual. It is 
the imperfect nature of Latvia's laws, in which the concept of 
"collaboration" is in need of clarification, and also the 
reaction in the country to his open letter in which he described 
what his contacts with the KGB had been, that made the minister 
decide to resign. 
  As already reported, Latvian laws do not permit those who 
collaborated with the KGB to be deputies or occupy certain state 
posts. 

</TEXT>

