<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Round of Free Trade Negotiations With EU Closes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Round of Free Trade Negotiations With EU Closes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0706101994 Tallinn ETA in English 1744 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0706101994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["News Release"] </F>
  [Text] Estonian delegation at Estonian-European Union free 
trade negotiations, after returning from Brussels, gave a news 
conference saying progress had been made while several issues 
remained to be discussed further. 
  Latvia has closed the negotiations and is ready to initial 
the agreement, the head of the Estonian delegation, Priit 
Kolbre, said. 
  The main problems between Estonia and EU are in the field of 
textiles, Signe Ratso from the Estonian Economics Ministry said. 
Estonia is opposed to the double check system EU requests which 
would mean that Estonia should impose administrative control 
over all textile products moving to European markets. That 
contradicts Estonia's economics policy and understanding of free 
trade, Ratso added. Besides, imposing such mechanisms and 
issuing licenses is very costly. At the moment, Estonia enjoys 
tariff- and quota-free access to European markets, Priit Pallum 
from the Economics Ministry remarked. 
  Another field under negotiations were fishery, customs and 
agriculture. 
  Estonia is satisfied with the results achieved in the 
fishery 
group and, hopefully, EU member countries will accept the 
quotas, Lauri Vaarja, head of the Estonian Fishery Board, said. 
  The negotiation on agricultural produce must also continue 
as 
Estonia views conditions included in the protocol on market 
protection system unfavourable, deputy chancellor of the 
Ministry of Agriculture, Ruve Shank, said. Shank also said 
Estonia opposed the so-called joint Baltic quota proposed by the 
EU which would mean that the country which is the first to bring 
its check-up systems to European level would benefit most of the 
quotas. 
  Estonian-EU free trade agreement is expected to be 
initialled 
in the beginning of July and signed in October or November. In 
that case it can take effect on January 1, 1995 as planned. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39218 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov109_v_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-109 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Brazauskas Signs Law on Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Brazauskas Signs Law on Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0706102094 Tallinn BNS in English 1805 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0706102094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jun 06, BNS -- Lithuanian President 
Algirdas Brazauskas on Monday signed the recently adopted law on 
government, which comes into effect next week. 
  In his traditional Monday radio interview this week, 
Brazauskas said outlays on government will not increase, 
although the number of ministries will grow from 16 to 19. 
  The president said changes within the Cabinet do not mean 
that a government of experts will be replaced by government of 
politicians. Brazauskas emphasized that ministers must be both 
politicians and experts. 
  Commenting on the creation of the new Environment Protection 
Ministry instead of the currently existing department, which is 
subordinate to the parliament, Brazauskas said it is not normal 
that an institution of the executive branch belongs to the 
legislative branch. Besides, he said, such ministries exist in 
nearly all countries around the Baltic Sea. Similar structures 
should deal with such problems as pollution of the sea, 
Brazauskas said. 
  Discussing division of the Culture and Education Ministry 
into two separate ministries, the president said these 
institutions were merged artificially and the step proved to be 
incorrect. 
  In Brazauskas' words, the new Municipal Affairs Ministry 
will 
not be very big, but is needed to carry out government reforms 
"from the top to the bottom." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

