<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Insistence on 14th Army Pullout by 1 Jul </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    No Insistence on 14th Army Pullout by 1 Jul </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606164694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1312 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chisinau will not insist on the complete withdrawal 
of Russia's 14th Army from Moldova before 1 July 1994, as this 
term is unreal, head of the Moldovan delegation, Deputy Foreign 
Minister Nikolai Osmokesku told INTERFAX before his departure 
for Moscow, where the ninth round of the Moldovan-Russian talks 
on the status of the 14th Army and the schedule of its 
withdrawal will be held on 7 and 8 June. 
  He also announced that Chisinau would advance a number of 
new 
demands, including the demand that Russia pay Moldova a 
compensation for the 14th Army's stay from the moment it was put 
under Russia's jurisdiction. 
  The talks will also deal with the military transit through 
Ukraine during the withdrawal. Talks will be started with 
Ukraine as the third party concerned. 
  In addition to the main agreement, seven or eight additional 
agreements are expected to be signed. 

</TEXT>

