Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Euro-Atlantic Center Criticizes Snegur-Smirnov Declaration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Euro-Atlantic Center Criticizes Snegur-Smirnov Declaration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0606173494 Chisinau BASAPRESS in English 1811 GMT 4 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0606173494 </F>
<F P=104>  Chisinau BASAPRESS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chisinau BASAPRESS, 4/6/1994 -- "Some aspects of 
the declaration of Moldovan President Mircea Snegur and Tiraspol 
leader Igor Smirnov signed on 28 April contradict the basic 
principles of the opinion poll "La Sfat Cu Poporul" ("Consulting 
With the People") especially the article which affirms that 
Moldova is a unitary state," states an analytic report of the 
Moldovan Euro-Atlantic Center. The authors of the report 
consider that the term "juridical status of state for Dniester," 
can be interpreted as "the creation of a confederation union on 
the basis of an agreement between two autonomous entities with 
equal rights for sovereignty." References of the type 
"departing from the existing political reality," which are often 
used in the declaration, could serve as a definite juridical 
basis for the legalization of the illegitimate structures of 
Dniester, including the armed forces, says the report. The 
experts of the Euro-Atlantic Center consider that the 28 April 
declaration allows the leaders of the self-proclaimed Dniester 
republic to negotiate about the interests of Tiraspol without 
having to give up any positions. At the same time the authors 
of the report doubt the legitimacy of the signing of the 
declaration on the behalf of Dniester by the Russian citizen 
Igor Smirnov. According to the cited source, the definite 
refusal of Chisinau to allow the representatives of Romania and 
the Ukraine to participate in the solving of the Dniester 
conflict may lead to an aggravation in the relations between 
Moldova and these states. The experts of the Euro-Atlantic 
Center gauged the results of the 28 April negotiations as a 
voluntary passage of Moldova into the Russian area of interests, 
which could generate essential problems in its relations with 
the West, including economic ones. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

