<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Union Leader: `Atomic Industry on Brink of Stoppage' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Union Leader: `Atomic Industry on Brink of Stoppage' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606135394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1309 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606135394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Marina Barinova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 6 TASS -- "Russia's atomic industry is 
now on the brink of stoppage", Vladimir Startsev, chairman of 
the Central Committee of the Russian atomic energy industry 
trade union, told a news conference on Monday. He said that the 
precarious situation that developed in the nuclear energy 
complex resulted from non-payment by the Russian Grid 
joint-stock company for the electricity received from nuclear 
power stations. The company ran up a debt of 674 billion rubles. 
  Planned work to ensure safe operation of nuclear power 
stations had to be stopped because of the lack of funds. Unless 
the situation changes, the Balakovo nuclear power station will 
have to be shut down for safety reasons in June. The station's 
operators salaries are in arrears for three months. "Operators 
are despairing and the situation may get out of control any 
time", Startsev said. 
  The work of the entire nuclear fuel cycle is paralysed by 
the 
lack of funds, Lev Ryabev, Russian first deputy minister of 
nuclear power, told reporters. Production amalgamation 
"Mashinostritelny Zavod" stopped the manufacture of clusters of 
fuel elements. The Chepetsk mechanical plant producing 
zirconium was stopped. There is a similar situation at 
complexes in Krasnoyarsk-26, Tomsk-7, Kirovo-Chepetsk and at 
nuclear machine building plants. 
  It will be necessary to lower the capacity of power 
generating sets at nuclear stations to prolong their operation 
with the use of whatever fuel remains, Ryabev said. If a 
nuclear power plant is shut down, it will take seven to ten 
years for reactors to cool off. Fuel storages will have to be 
maintained in a safe state. This will require the consumption 
of large amounts of electricity, and hence huge outlays. 
  In view of the fact that funds needed for the maintenance of 
normal operation of stations are not allocated, the Russian 
Ministry of Nuclear Power Industry and the Central Committee of 
the trade union made a proposal to the State Duma to envisage 
the allocation to nuclear power stations of 560 billion rubles 
from the budget on easy terms when the Russian budget for 1994 
is finally drawn up. If this proposal is not accepted, it will 
take a much larger sum, over one thousand billion rubles, to 
shut off nuclear stations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

