<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Servicemen Union, Defense Ministry Sign Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Servicemen Union, Defense Ministry Sign Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0606112594 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 3 Jun 94 First 
Edition p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM0606112594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Nikolay Burbyga: "Independent Trade Union of </F>
Servicemen Makes Friends With Defense Ministry"] 
  [Text] A cooperation agreement has been signed between the 
independent trade union of servicemen and the Defense Ministry. 
  According to Mikhail Kolchev, chairman of the trade union, 
everyone will benefit from this step, but above all former 
military men who were forced to retire due to army cuts. This 
year alone more than 180,000 officers will be leaving the army, 
and each subsequent year the plan is to cut 50,000 officers. 
The independent trade union's task is to uphold these people's 
interests and provide them with social and legal protection. An 
agreement of this kind has been signed not only with the Defense 
Ministry, but with other power ministries as well. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39244 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov109_d_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-109 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chechen Politician Denounces Ban </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chechen Politician Denounces Ban </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606170794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1522 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606170794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [by ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 6 TASS -- Chechen opposition leader 
Yaragi Mamodayev denounced Sunday's decision by the Chechen 
government and parliament to ban former Russian parliament 
chairman Ruslan Khasbulatov from the republic. 
  The decision also affects former Chechen communist leader 
Doka Zavgayev. 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS on Monday, Mamodayev said 
that 
"instead of seeking reconciliation, Dudayev's regime takes steps 
causing the situation to worsen." 
  He also brushed off accusations of alleged involvement, 
together with Russia, in preparations to remove Dzhokhar Dudayev 
from power. "We do not want confrontation or opposition between 
various parts of the Chechen population. We call for 
reconciliation and political dialogue," he said. 
  Mamodayev stressed that the way out from the current crisis 
is through a constructive dialogue and the soonest possible 
economic reform. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

