<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Scientist Opposes Sanctions Against DPRK, Urges Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Scientist Opposes Sanctions Against DPRK, Urges Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606145194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1404 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Dmitriy Gorokhov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 6 TASS -- All diplomatic instruments of 
the United Nations should be put to use to settle the situation 
in the Korean peninsula by political means and to keep from a 
rash resort to sanctions. This view was stated to ITAR-TASS on 
Monday by Professor Anatoliy Torkunov, one of leading Russian 
experts on Korea who heads the Moscow State Institute of 
International Relations. 
  Torkunov said demands of the international community to 
North 
Korea are fair. The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
does not require of North Korea anything beyond what it expects 
from other countries. Russia fully shares this attitude to the 
nuclear problem which is the root-cause of the present Korean 
crisis. Russian approach was set out in detail during the 
negotiations Russian President Boris Yeltsin held with President 
of the Republic of Korea Kim Young-sam in Moscow the other day. 
  The Russian scientist warned against a rash recource to 
sanctions. Pyongyang got accustomed to relying on its own 
resources. Sanctions can only lead to the further spiral of 
ideological confrontation which, in the long run, will affect 
the position of ordinary Koreans. The further heightening of 
tension is fraught with unpredictable consequences as the Korean 
peninsula is inundated with arms in its both parts. 
  An international conference in the Korean peninsula 
suggested 
by Russia could be an effective way of easing the situation, 
Professor Torkunov believes. An ever greater interest is now 
shown in this idea as it essentially meets the interest of all 
the parties, including North Korea. The conference could put an 
end to the isolation of North Korea which has been increasing of 
late. South Korea has succeeded in establishing diplomatic 
relations with Russia, China and East european countries in the 
recent years. Meanwhile North Korea does not have diplomatic 
relations with the United States and others leading Western 
countries. If an international conference is held, Pyongyang 
could get real diplomatic levers to protect its own interests. 
North Korea should realise that the factor of menace to South 
Korea is no longer as important as it used to be. South Korea 
has a strong army, and Seoul interacts in defence matters with 
the United States on a basis on a treaty. 
  All the parties concerned should use every method of 
persuasion. China has levers of influence too. Beijing has 
traditional ramified ties with Pyongyang. Tokyo has levers of 
influence as trade with Japan is important for North Korea as an 
outlet to the Western world. 
  Russia must be flexible on this matter, Torkunov said. 
Russia has a certain stretch of common border with North Korea, 
and power politics in relations with neighbours can hardly be 
expedient. This is why the Russian line is to coordinate 
diplomatic efforts with other countries. Possibilities of a 
political settlement have not been exhausted, Torkunov said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39280 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov109_a_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-109 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Cites Clinton on `Unanimous' Stance on DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Paper Cites Clinton on `Unanimous' Stance on DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0606152894 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 7 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM0606152894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Vladimir Nadein report: "Russia, the United States, and </F>
China Unanimous in Demands on North Korea"] 
  [Text] President Bill Clinton has said that the United 
States, Russia, and China are unanimous in the opinion that the 
armament of North Korea with nuclear missiles must be prevented 
and can unite the whole world community around themselves in 
imposing economic sanctions on Pyongyang. 
  This opinion was voiced in an interview which the U.S. 
President gave to Tom Brokaw, a leading NBC TV commentator, on 
board a U.S. warship off the Normandy coast. Clinton defended 
his administration's foreign policy, claiming that it takes a 
long time to elaborate a long-term foreign policy because the 
world situation since the end of the Cold War is not black and 
white and is completely unparalleled. 
  "The main thing is that we have not gone away, we have 
become 
involved (in maintaining international peace)," the president 
said, speaking about the foreign policy strategy which will soon 
be presented to the public. 
  In Clinton's opinion, the DPRK has no grounds for 
considering 
an economic blockade an act of war and will not take actions 
against South Korea or Japan. In reply to Tom Brokaw's question 
on whether the administration's indecision over Bosnia and Haiti 
will not have the effect of toughening Pyongyang's position, 
Clinton said that he believes that this will not happen because 
North Korea "will get a very clear signal" from the group of 
states interested in observing the principles of the 
nonproliferation of nuclear weapons. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

