<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on ROK President's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on ROK President's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Meets Russian, Korean Businessmen </H4>

<F P=102> LD0306211394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2010 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0306211394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Nikolay Geronin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 3 TASS -- A meeting of South Korean 
President Kim Yong-sam with Russian and South Korean businessmen 
was held today at Moscow's Metropol Hotel to discuss ways to 
upgrade bilateral economic relations. 
  The meeting was attended by First Russian Vice-Premier Oleg 
Soskovets and vice-premier, Minister of Economy Aleksandr 
Shokhin, President of the Russian Union of Industrialists and 
Entrepreneurs Arkadiy Volskiy and President of the South Korean 
Daewoo concern Kim Woo Jung. 
  The South Korean president made a brief speech to urge a 
boost to bilateral economic cooperation. 
  The head of the Daewoo concern told ITAR-TASS that bilateral 
economic cooperation is promising. At the same time, there are 
certain obstacles on the way of more active South Korean 
businesses in Russia, including the absence of a clear legal 
basis for activities of foreign companies in Russia. 
  The imperfect Russian legislation slows down the 
participation of foreign firms in development of Russian 
economy, President of the Russian Union of Industrialists and 
Entrepreneurs Volskiy told ITAR- TASS. 
  Other Commonwealth republics have adopted laws on protection 
of foreign investments from political risks and guarantees of 
the right to export revenues. That is why, some foreign 
companies leave Russia for Uzbekistan and Kazakhstan. For 
instance, the Daewoo concern has started to build a car plant in 
the Uzbek city of Namangan with an overall production capacity 
of 200,000 cars and vans a year. 
  At the same time, there are possibilities to boost 
Russian-South Korean economic relations, said Volskiy. There 
are plenty of South Korean proposals to participate in 
corporatization of Russian plants. A gas pipeline from Yakutia 
to South Korea is being discussed. The Daewoo concern and the 
St. Petersburg Pozitron plant have signed an agreement on 
production of video cassette players. 

</TEXT>

