<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul, Moscow Agree on Closer Technology Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seoul, Moscow Agree on Closer Technology Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0306131294 Seoul YONHAP in English 1219 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0306131294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, June 3 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and Russia on 
Friday [3 June] afternoon agreed to expedite the transfer of 
Russia's high-tech expertise to South Korea in the areas of 
aeronautical materials, airplane engine and energy. 
  At the fourth joint Korea-Russia science and technology 
committee meeting, the two countries decided to establish 
research centers of the three areas in Moscow with the 
participation of research institutes and industries of the two 
countries. 
  South Korea was represented at the meeting by Science and 
Technology Minister Kim Si-chung who was accompanying President 
Kim Yong-sam to the Moscow visit, and Russia by Science and 
Technology Policy Minister Boris Saltykov. 
  The joint institutes the two ministers agreed on are a 
Korea-Russia aeronautical materials research center, a 
Korea-Russia airplane engine research center and a Korea-Russia 
energy research center. 
  The idea of the two ministers is that the two countries 
jointly develop new technology in Moscow through these research 
centers and that Russia would accelerate the transfer of 
high-tech expertise it possesses to South Korea. 

</TEXT>

