<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow To Supply More Low-Enriched Uranium To ROK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow To Supply More Low-Enriched Uranium To ROK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306193294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1810 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0306193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia is prepared to increase supplies of 
low-enriched uranium to South Korea from the present 40 tonnes 
to 100 tonnes per year, Russian First Vice-Premier Oleg 
Soskovets said at a meeting with that country's Minister for 
Trade, Industry and Energy Kim Chol-Su in Moscow Friday. 
  To quote Soskovets, Russia was ready to increase coal 
supplies to South Korea from 400,000 to 1.5-2 million tonnes. 
Moscow, he said, was willing to form a joint venture with South 
Korea in the Neryungri coal field in Yakutia and grant the 
Korean side the right of ownership of a section of that deposit. 
  Soskovets said South Korea was making "only negligible" 
investments in Russian industry (a mere 27 million US dollars 
last year). 
  Soskovets stressed that Russia was a dependable partner and 
Korean private companies which invested in Russian industry 
would receive dividends. 

</TEXT>

