<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade With Heilongjiang `Dropped Drastically' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade With Heilongjiang `Dropped Drastically' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706092094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0910 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706092094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Spirin] </F>
  [Text] Beijing June 7 TASS -- Russia's main trade partner 
in China -- the province of Heilongjiang -- is reconsidering its 
foreign economic priorities and planning to switch over from 
Russia to the rapidly developing countries of Southeast Asia. 
  According to Heilongjiang Vice-Governor Wang Zhongzhang, 
quoted by the "HONGKONG CHINA NEWS AGENCY", the province is 
bound to revise its foreign economic strategy shortly with due 
account of "the new situation in the region". 
  The heavy industry of this northeastern province, which 
borders on the Russian Far East and the Russian maritime 
territory, was built up with Soviet assistance in the fifties. 
It now accounts for an important share of the country's heavy 
industry. This is why the province was traditionally linked by 
close economic ties with its northern neighbour. However, trade 
between Heilongjiang and Russia had dropped drastically in the 
first quarter of this year -- by almost 45 per cent. This is 
partially due to Moscow's decision to impose visa restrictions 
on the entry of Chinese into the Russian Federation and also due 
to the growth of customs duties. 
  Since Russia is short of convertible money, needed to trade 
with China, Wang Zhongzhang said, Beijing has already taken 
measures to limit the import of Russian raw materials and 
semifinished goods, for instance, steel rolled stock. 
  As to Heilongjiang firms, which are in great straits due to 
the state sector's growing debt, they were recommended to seek 
"new external sources of financial revenues", primarily in 
Southeast Asian countries, where local Chinese businessmen have 
much weight. 
  The volume of Russo-Chinese trade amounted to approximately 
6.7 billion U.S. dollars in 1993 and Heilongjiang Province 
accounted for its lion's share. 
  It is not without reason that Moscow had always praised this 
Chinese province. Three of its high-ranking officials were 
decorated in 1992 with Russian "people's friendship" orders for 
their "large contribution to the development of Russo-Chinese 
friendship". 

</TEXT>

