<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Returns from Geneva; Nikiforov Stands In </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Returns from Geneva; Nikiforov Stands In </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606132894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1258 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606132894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, June 6 (TANJUG) -- Russian Deputy Foreign 
Minister Vitaliy Churkin returned to Moscow from Geneva on 
Monday. 
  Standing in for him at talks on peace for Bosnia on Monday 
will be ranking Foreign Ministry official Aleksey Nikiforov. 
  Nikiforov is Russia's representative to the international 
`contact group' for Bosnia, which comprises also the United 
States and the European Union. 
  The `contact group' insists that Bosnia's warring Moslems, 
Serbs and Croats end hostilities and seek solutions to their 
dispute through talks, which should pave the way for dividing 
Bosnia by giving 51 per cent of the territory to the Moslems and 
Croats for their federation and 49 per cent to the Serbs. 
  The `contact group' was due to meet with representatives of 
Bosnia's belligerents last weekend, but the meeting was not held. 
  Churkin was originally scheduled to brief the press at the 
Foreign Ministry in Moscow on Monday, but the briefing has been 
cancelled. 
  It is not certain when Churkin may meet the press because of 
a busy schedule, TANJUG learns at the Russian Foreign Ministry. 

</TEXT>

