Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin on Representatives in Normandy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin on Representatives in Normandy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606170694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1544 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606170694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian President Boris Yeltsin does not share the 
opinion that the absence of Russian representatives at the 
celebration of the fiftieth anniversary of the allied landing in 
Normandy proves that the West still did not trust Russia. 
Yeltsin said this today after he had bought a book by well 
known Russian poet Alexander Pushkin in a bookshop in Tverskaya 
Street (to mark the 195th anniversary of Pushkin's birth). 
  Yeltsin repeated that on June 6 the celebrations in Normandy 
had just begun and each town in Normandy would celebrate the day 
of its own liberation from fascists. Yeltsin announced that the 
Russian delegation had been invited to one of the Normandy towns 
on June 28-29. 
  Yeltsin underlined that established tradition was also of 
importance. "When we were celebrating the fiftieth anniversary 
of the battles around Moscow and Stalingrad, etc., we did not 
invite any of our allies either. However, this does not stop us 
from being partners in all spheres, from trusting each other, 
respecting each other and resolving together international 
problems," Yeltsin emphasized. 
  Yeltsin confirmed his intention to meet Russian writer 
Alexander Solzhenitsyn. Currently, Solzhenitsyn is visiting the 
Russian Far East. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

