<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Archives Throw Light on Fate of U.S. MIA's </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Archives Throw Light on Fate of U.S. MIA's </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0306170794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1630 GMT 3 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0306170794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lilia Kuznetsova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 3 TASS -- The testimony of eyewitnesses 
and access to archive materials have thrown additional light on 
the fate of American servicemen reported missing during World 
War II on the territory of the Soviet Union, according to the 
members of the joint Russian-American commission. The 
commission, created to study the problem of American missing, 
held a press-conference on Friday to discuss the results of its 
latest plenary session. 
  Co-Chairman of the commission Dmitriy Volkogonov declared 
that the group's work has reached a new level and taken on an 
international character. The embassies of Great Britain, 
Australia, and Italy appealed to the commission today to help 
them learn more about their missing servicemen. Volkogonov said 
the group's work was "very important evidence of the improvement 
in relations between Russia and the USA." 
  Congressman Pete Peterson, co-chairman of the commission 
from 
the American side, noted that their work has been based 
exclusively on facts and personal testimony. The "cold war" 
group was able to uncover the remains of American pilot John 
Robertson Dunham, who was shot down over the Soviet Union in 
October 1952. New information about the pilots shot down in 
April 1950 and September 1952 has also been gathered. 
  The commission's sub-group for the Korean war has been able 
to get new information from Russian archives, and even the 
intelligence archives were opened up to shed more light on the 
Vietnam war. 
  The commission also noted that the American side has been 
able to provide the Russians some additional clues concerning 
Russian servicemen reported missing in Afghanistan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

