<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Studies Russian Proposal on Korean Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC Studies Russian Proposal on Korean Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0606121894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1204 GMT 6 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0606121894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Pavel Spirin and Vyacheslav </F>
Tomilin] 
  [Text] Beijing June 6 TASS -- China intends to "seriously" 
study the Russian proposal on holding an international 
conference on the nuclear problem of the Korean peninsula, but 
believes it is better to solve it through talks between 
Pyongyang, the International Atomic Energy Agency, the USA and 
South Korea, according to a spokesman of the Chinese Foreign 
Ministry. 
  "We have taken into consideration the Russian-proposed 
idea", 
he told TASS on Monday, but added that, according to the Chinese 
Government, "the most efficient and practical variant of solving 
the problem is to hold bilateral consultations in three 
directions: North Korea - the IAEA, North Korea - the United 
States, and Pyongyang - Seoul". 
  Beijing is conducting an active dialogue with the North 
Korean leadership on its nuclear programme, according to sources 
close to diplomatic circles. It strives to preserve "special 
relations" between the two countries and at the same time to 
exert influence on its partner in order to settle the conflict 
without any sanctions. 
  It is noteworthy that last Saturday the North Korean 
ambassador in China has resolutely rejected the Russian idea 
about the international conference. The nuclear free status of 
the peninsula should be discussed only in a close circle - 
between North Korea and the United States. 
  However, the Hong Kong-based "TA KUNG PAO" newspaper is sure 
that China can join economic sanctions against Pyongyang. It 
believes Beijing can cease shipments of food and oil. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

