<H3> <TI>   PRC Opposes Sanctions Against DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC Opposes Sanctions Against DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706105694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0953 
GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0706105694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Andrey Kirillov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 7 Jun -- China does not support the 
imposition of economic sanctions on the DPRK because this 
measure "can only lead to an escalation of tensions on the 
Korean peninsula." This was said today in an interview with the 
ITAR-TASS correspondent by Sui Tsin, minister-counsellor at the 
Chinese embassy in Moscow. He described reports in the Hong 
Kong press about the possibility of China joining the sanctions 
as untrustworthy. 
  China has limited influence on the DPRK, the diplomat added, 
and it depends on the Koreans themselves whether North Korea 
finally accepts the IAEA's demands concerning its nuclear 
program. 
  The Chinese diplomat spoke in favor of continuing 
negotiations and looking for compromises. 

</TEXT>

