<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japan Rejects Proposal for Conference on Korea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japan Rejects Proposal for Conference on Korea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706063794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0504 
GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0706063794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vasiliy Golovnin] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo, 7 Jun--An executive staff member of the 
Japanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs told an ITAR-TASS 
correspondent today that Tokyo does not think that it makes any 
sense in the current situation to seriously study Russia's 
proposal on holding an international conference on the Korean 
peninsula with the participation of the two Korean states, 
China, the Russian Federation, the United States, Japan, the 
United Nations, and the International Atomic Energy Agency. 
  He noted that Tokyo now intends to achieve a solution to the 
problem of Pyongyang's nuclear program primarily on the basis of 
close consultations with the United States and South Korea. The 
Government of Japan, the member of the Foreign Ministry staff 
stated, also places hope in the upcoming session of the UN 
Security Council relating to this issue. On Monday, Tokyo 
officially announced that it is prepared to join in the 
sanctions against the Korean People's Democratic Republic, 
within the framework of its Constitution, if the United Nations 
agrees to this measure. 
  Earlier, Pyongyang itself did, in fact, reject Moscow's 
proposal that an international conference should be held to 
settle the tension on the peninsula, having confirmed its 
intention to discuss with the United States alone the issue of 
its nuclear program and the possible complete withdrawal from 
the system of the treaty on the nonproliferation of nuclear 
weapons. 
  To all appearances, Washington is also taking a passive 
attitude toward Russia's initiative, although President Bill 
Clinton has also stated that it would possibly make sense to 
implement it if events were to develop in a certain way. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

