<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Indian Foreign Minister Satisfied With Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Indian Foreign Minister Satisfied With Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706204194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1229 
GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0706204194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Zakharchenko for </F>
KAZTAG] 
  [Text] Almaty, 7 June -- "The main goal of my visit is to 
speed up the implementation of the accords between the two 
states which were attained earlier," Salman Khurshid, India's 
minister of state for external affairs, said at a press 
conference here today after completing his visit to Kazakhstan. 
  "We have seen once again," the minister said, "that 
Kazakhstan leadership adheres to the strengthening of ties with 
India and the development of mutually beneficial cooperation of 
businessmen from both countries." He noted with satisfaction 
that a business council to coordinate joint activity had been 
set up. A solemn ceremony to inaugurate an Indian cultural 
center will be held in Almaty soon, and an Indian restaurant 
will open. By late June, regular Almaty- Delhi flights will 
start, something to boost bilateral relations even further. 
  "During the visit," Salman Khurshid stressed, "mutual 
understanding of the need to sign accords on avoiding double 
taxation of exported goods and providing firm guarantees for 
investments took shape." He expressed the confidence that 
Kazakhstan and India would actively cooperate in many 
international organizations to secure peace and stability on the 
Asian continent. 
  The Indian delegation left Almaty for Bishkek today. 

</TEXT>

