<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Experts' Doubt Parliament's Reform Abilities </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Experts' Doubt Parliament's Reform Abilities </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706132194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1224 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Akimov] </F>
  [Text] Almaty 7 June TASS -- An overwhelming majority of 
experts do not believe in the reforming ability of the Kazakh 
Parliament and many do not rule it out that it will be dissolved 
soon, according to an opinion poll taken by the Almaty Centre 
for Humanitarian Studies among Kazakh political scientists, 
leaders of public movements and political parties, ranking civil 
servants and prominent journalists. 
  The findings of the poll, published on Tuesday [7 June], 
indicate that 61.8 percent of respondents believe that the 
Kazakhstan parliament in its present composition will not be 
able to act as a catalyst of reforms in society, 44.1 percent of 
experts maintain that the deputies corps has a low level of 
political culture, and 41.2 percent explain their attitude by 
the parliamentarians' estrangement from the electorate due to 
various kinds of irregularities during the parliamentary 
elections and the imperfection of the electoral system. 
  The opinion of 61.8 percent of experts is that the election 
campaign was of an utterly undemocratic nature, and 44.1 percent 
of respondents do not rule out the probability that the Kazakh 
Parliament will be dissolved soon. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

