<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Monetary Merger With Russia Possible Until Late 1994 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    No Monetary Merger With Russia Possible Until Late 1994 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806090494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0827 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806090494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Gridneva] </F>
  [Text] Dushanbe 8 June TASS -- "Full merger of the Russian 
and Tajik monetary systems can be achieved no sooner than by the 
end of this year," said Tajik Economics and Planning Minister, 
Rustam Mirzoyev, in an interview with ITAR-TASS. Mirzoyev 
pointed out that not only a political decision to this effect 
was adopted by the heads of the two countries, but a package of 
documents, concerning the second stage of the merger, was worked 
out and submitted to Russian colleagues. 
  The minister pointed out that there are no serious opponents 
to the unification of the two monetary systems either in Russia, 
or in Tajikistan. The process of the monetary merger is very 
complex both technically and organizationally, he said. At the 
same time, Tajik manufacturers should work hard to step up the 
process. It is necessary to earn Russian roubles ourselves by 
increasing supplies of industrial products and raw materials, 
i.e. to give priority in exports policy to Russia, the Tajik 
minister said. 
  According to Mirzoyev, Tajikistan faces severe cash 
shortages 
and the government is 170 billion roubles in debt to the 
population. The remaining 25 billion roubles expected to arrive 
from Russia as part of the 120-billion credit to Tajikistan will 
not be enough even to pay pensions and social allowances, he 
said. 
  Asked by ITAR-TASS if Tajikistan intends to introduce 
temporary money for internal payments, the minister declined to 
answer, saying that such problems are in the competence of the 
Tajik parliament. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

