<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abkhazia Denies Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Abkhazia Denies Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706171194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1435 
GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0706171194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Ostanin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 7 Jun -- So far not a single subunit of the 
CIS or the UN peacekeeping forces has entered Abkhaz territory. 
Some media reports that such subunits have started to arrive at 
the Georgian-Abkhaz line of confrontation are not true. The 
ITAR-TASS correspondent has learned this at the press office of 
the Abkhaz Supreme Soviet today. 
  As everyone knows, the legislative bodies of the CIS states 
have not yet made any decision on the introduction of 
peacekeeping forces into the zone of conflict. 
  In accordance with the Georgian-Abkhaz agreements on a 
cease-fire and separation of the forces, which were signed in 
Moscow on 14 May, the peacekeeping forces will be deployed in 
the 12-kilometer-long strip of the security zone. The agreement 
also provides for the opposing sides to deploy armed formations, 
except for heavy combat machinery, in the zone where a limited 
range of arms is permitted. The peacekeeping forces will be 
expected to patrol the Kodor gorge as well. 
  As the press office has noted, following the arrival of the 
peacekeeping forces, the UN observers can leave the security 
zone, if necessary, provided they agree on this with the leaders 
of the opposing sides. 
  [Tbilisi CONTACT INFORMATION AGENCY in Russian at 1310 GMT 
on 
7 June carries a similar report stating the following: "Russian 
mass media reported today, quoting Abkhaz sources, that the 
deployment of CIS peacekeeping forces in the conflict zone in 
Abkhazia has already begun. However, this was not confirmed by 
the Georgian Defense Ministry."] 

</TEXT>

