<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Elections in `Explosive' Western Areas To Go Ahead </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Elections in `Explosive' Western Areas To Go Ahead </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0706131094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 7 Jun 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK0706131094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed NEGA report in the "Georgia" column] </F>
  [Text] On 12 June elections to the Georgian republic 
parliament will be held in another three hitherto explosive 
areas of western Georgia -- Zugdidi, Tsalendzhik, and 
Tskhorotskusk. Each district will elect one deputy. (In 
October 1992, when Georgia-wide parliamentary elections were 
held, they did not take place in these areas owing to a 
complicated sociopolitical situation. At that time the 
districts were controlled by armed supporters of Zviad 
Gamsakhurdia). 
  Among the six deputies running for one seat in the Zugdidi 
district is Georgian Prime Minister Otari Patsatsiya. Born in 
Zugdidi, he held responsible economic and state posts in the 
district for several years. Many observers believe that Otari 
Patsatsiya will win these elections in the Zugdidi district, 
where his efforts to stabilize the situation in November 1993 
are well remembered. 
  On 12 June, elections will also take place in the city of 
Rustavi in eastern Georgia. Zhiuli Shartava, Georgian 
parliament deputy from this city, was assassinated on 27 
September 1993 by Abkhaz militants during the storming of 
Sukhumi. At the time he was chairman of the Council of 
Ministers of the Abkhaz Autonomous Republic. 
  Generally, the issue of elections in Georgia is very acute. 
Some political parties propose that early parliamentary 
elections be held, considering it important to renew the 
parliament composition. Other parties believe that there is no 
need to hold elections to the Georgian parliament until 
Georgia's jurisdiction has been established over the territory 
of Abkhazia and South Ossetia. 

</TEXT>

