<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin, Luzhkov, Soskovets Lead Popularity Poll </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin, Luzhkov, Soskovets Lead Popularity Poll </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806115794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1112 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806115794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow June 8 ITAR-TASS -- A monthly poll conducted 
by the Association of Political and Economic Experts on order 
from "THE NEW DAILY" has revealed that President Boris Yeltsin, 
Moscow Mayor Yuriy Luzhkov, and First Vice-Premier Oleg 
Soskovets are at top of the list of the most influential 
politicians in Russia in May. 
  These leaders scored 54.5, 52.625, and 50.25 points 
respectively. They are closely followed by Premier Viktor 
Chernomyrdin (49.75), Central Bank Governor Viktor Gerashchenko 
(48.125), Yeltsin's body-guard chief Aleksandr Korzhakov 
(47.75), State Duma Chairman Ivan Rybkin (47.625), National 
Security Council Secretary Oleg Lobov (46.75), Federation 
Council Chairman Vladimir Shumeyko (44.5), and the president's 
first aide Viktor Ilyushin (44.125). 
  The list published in today's issue of THE NEW DAILY 
comprises 50 names. The newspaper explains that they are the 
names of the leading politicians, including the leaders of 
parties and political movements, executive and legislative 
bodies of power, information and commercial structures in 
command of considerable resources and opportunities for making 
political and state decisions and ensuring their realization. 
  According to experts, regional leaders and officials of the 
military-industrial complex "are now on the offensive". 
  "The modest and quiet Rybkin is today's real alternative to 
the president," they say. "Unless, of course, the left-wingers 
and the patriots agree to support a common candidate, as 
proposed by the Communist Party leader Gennadiy Zyuganov. The 
largest faction in the State Duma is controlled not by the 
Liberal-Democratic Party of Russia (50 deputies), and not by 
Russia's Choice (70), but by the coalition of Communists and 
Agrarians (100 deputies). 
  "Sergey Shakhray's rating has not declined as expected" 
after 
his dismissal from the post of the minister of nationalities and 
regional policy, the newspaper says. "Shakhray is an 
independent figure and his time is not past," the newspaper 
concludes. 

</TEXT>

