<H3> <TI>   Justice Ministry Registers `New Names' Movement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Justice Ministry Registers `New Names' Movement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK0806084094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 8 Jun 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> MK0806084094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Gleb Cherkasov report under the "Continuers" rubric: "`New </F>
Names' Casts Off `Russia's Future'"] 
  [Text] The electoral association "Russia's Future -- New 
Names," which failed to clear the 5-percent hurdle in the race 
for deputy seats, now has a successor. The other day the 
Justice Ministry registered an interregional movement calling 
itself "New Names," which has been joined by some participants 
in the electoral bloc of the same name, including federal ticket 
leaders Vladimir Mironov, director of the Institute of Politics; 
and Oleg Sokolov, chairman of the youth organization of the 
Russian Social Democratic People's Party. At the same time, 
Vyacheslav Lashchevskiy, chairman of the Russian Youth Union, 
who used to head the electoral bloc, will not take part in the 
forming of the new organization. "New Names" intends to adhere 
to a social democratic trend and keep in touch with all public 
political associations far removed from extremism. 
  To date, "New Names" has six regional organizations in 
Tataria [Tatarstan], Bashkiria [Bashkortostan], and Tambov, 
among other places. According to "New Names" spokesman Artem 
Smolyannoy, primary organizations were set up in those regions 
where the electoral association managed more than 5 percent of 
the vote. Mr. Smolyannoy pointed out that although many 
activists of "Rutskoy's Party" participate in the work of the 
new organization, most of the participants in the project have 
nothing to do with the Russian Social Democratic People's Party. 
This perhaps explains why "New Names" is quite ready to accede 
to the Treaty on Accord. (Their signature is not there yet 
because they have not been invited to add it). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

