<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Latest on Privatization, Chubays-Luzhkov Controversy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Latest on Privatization, Chubays-Luzhkov Controversy </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Voucher Privatization Process To End 30 Jun </H4>

<F P=102> LD0806120694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1114 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806120694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Galkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 8 TASS -- "We shall not prolong the 
voucher privatisation," head of the Russian state property 
committee Anatoliy Chubays told a press conference here today. 
This means that the ongoing voucher privatisation process will 
end on June 30. Chubays stressed that "it will be rounded off 
with flying colours by June." 
  He told the press conference that he signed an order today 
to 
auction off 63 enterprises, which will be sold for privatisation 
vouchers. They include the "Apatite" production society, the 
Leningrad "Svetlana" association, the "Beryozka" trade house, 
and the "Norilsk Nickel" concern". This will allow the future 
share-holders to make use of their remaining vouchers. As many 
as 126 million vouchers out of the issued 148 millions have 
already been used. Chubays noted that the actual size of 
dividends received for invested privatisation vouchers proved to 
be not as fantastic as initially expected. They fluctuate from 
10 to 200 percent a year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

