<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Inflation in May Lowest Since Aug 1992 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Inflation in May Lowest Since Aug 1992 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0806100794 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 8 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM0806100794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Irina Goryacheva of Economic Conditions Center </F>
under Russian Federation Government under the "From Our 
Correspondents and News Agencies" rubric: "Forecast Not Borne 
Out: Inflation Proved Less Than Expected"] 
  [Text] The level of inflation in May was lower than 
forecast and stood at 8.1 percent. 
  Such a low inflation indicator has not been observed in 
Russia since August 1992. Foodstuffs went up 7.7 percent last 
month, nonfood commodities 8.1 percent, and paid services for 
the population 11.3 percent. The biggest increase in consumer 
prices (14.1 percent) was noted in the Ural Region, where the 
largest increases were in the prices of foodstuffs (13.6 
percent) and paid services for the population (36.5 percent). 
The smallest increase in the prices of basic consumer goods and 
services was in the Northern Region -- 5.9 percent. The 
increase in the prices of consumer goods and services stood at 
8.5 percent in Moscow and 7.9 percent in St. Petersburg. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

