<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Consumer Prices Rise 9.7 Percent in May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Consumer Prices Rise 9.7 Percent in May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806123094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1221 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806123094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By BUSINESS-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 8 TASS -- The index of consumer prices 
grew by 9.7 per cent in May, including food products -- by 11.7 
per cent, and non-food commodities -- by 6.5 per cent, BUSINESS 
TASS was told at the economic reforms working centre under the 
government of the Russian Federation. Prices for services grew 
by the largest margin of 12.7 per cent. 
  Prices went up particularly for apples and vegetables in 
May, 
whereas the cost of potatoes dropped by 1.3 per cent, and for 
eggs -- by 0.5 per cent. 
  The cost of a food basket, including 19 staple food 
products, 
grew on the average by 12.6 per cent throughout Russia. 
However, this indicator was much higher than the average in the 
east Siberian region, where it equalled to 21 per cent, and in 
the Urals -- 19.9 per cent. Prices went up only by 4.3 per cent 
in the Russian Far East. 

</TEXT>

