<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Agrees To Boost Defense Spending </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Agrees To Boost Defense Spending </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806140994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1329 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806140994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia's Government has approved the Duma Budget 
Committee's proposal to boost this year's defense spending from 
37.1 trillion to 40. 6 trillion rubles. 
  As INTERFAX has learned from parliamentary sources, that was 
revealed at a closed session of the Federal Assembly's lower 
house on Wednesday by Deputy Premier Aleksandr Shokhin. 
  The First Deputy Defence Minister Andrey Kokoshin insisted 
on 
a 55-trillion-ruble defense budget. 
  According to Grigoriy Yavlinskiy, leading the Yabloko 
parliamentary faction, there has been no debate on the issue. 
The Duma backed up the Legislation Committee Chairman Vladimir 
Isakov's proposal to speed up budget bill debates by voting on 
the whole package of amendments recommended by the budget 
committee. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

