<H3> <TI>   Cosmos-2281 Satellite in Flight </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cosmos-2281 Satellite in Flight </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706123194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1222 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706123194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS string correspondent Semen Ivanov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 7 TASS -- A Cosmos-2,281 satellite was 
launched from Plesetsk cosmodrome by a Soyuz-U booster rocket by 
Russia's space defence forces at 11.20 moscow time (07.20 GMT) 
on Tuesday. 
  The launch was successful. This was the 415th launch since 
December 27, 1971 when the first booster rocket of this type was 
lofted into space, Major-General Anatoliy Ovchinnikov, director 
of the Plesetsk cosmodrome, told ITAR-TASS. Preparations are 
being finalised at the cosmodrome for the launch of a photon 
technological spacecraft which is to blast off in one week's 
time. 
  The photon is an automatic laboratory fitted out with a set 
of technical facilities to obtain organic and inorganic 
materials and substances with improved characteristics in zero 
gravity. Specialists from the French national space research 
centre take part in the preparations. 
  In view of the fact that the satellite, which was launched 
from Plesetsk on May 25, 1994, failed to reach orbit, its number 
was given to the satellite launched today. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

