<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meeting Proposed To Prevent Violations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meeting Proposed To Prevent Violations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806141194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1329 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806141194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The incident involving an American Lockheed C-130 
that violated the Russian air space on Tuesday and was forced to 
land by Russian Air Defence in Adler near Sochi is being studied 
in Washington where all the necessary information was sent. 
This was reported to Interfax on Wednesday by a spokesman for 
the Russian Foreign Ministry Grigoriy Karasin. 
  In his opinion, Americans should be given time to study the 
circumstances. After that it would be logical to hold a meeting 
of high-ranking experts from Russia and the U.S. to prevent such 
incidents in the future, Karasin said. 
  As Interfax reported, the American plane was flying from 
Frankfurt-am-Main to Tbilisi. No requests were made for its 
flight across Russian territory. 
  On Tuesday evening the Russian Deputy Foreign Minister 
Anatoliy Adamishin sent a note to the American ambassador in 
Moscow Thomas Pickering. He hoped that the American side would 
apply disciplinary measures to those responsible. 
  Meanwhile, the main air traffic control center of Georgia 
has 
told Interfax that it is in no way responsible for the incident 
involving the American plane as it is does not belong to Georgia. 

</TEXT>

