<DOCNO> FBIS4-39428 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov110_a_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-110 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Affirms Support for Conference on DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow Affirms Support for Conference on DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806114894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0825 
GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0806114894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Vladimir Solntsev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 8 Jun (ITAR-TASS) -- Despite increasing 
pressure to impose sanctions against the DPRK which, allegedly, 
is developing its own nuclear weapons, Moscow maintains that 
this problem should be tackled by an international six-plus-two 
conference which has been suggested by Moscow. This was 
reiterated today by Russian Federation Deputy Foreign Minister 
Aleksandr Panov to an ITAR-TASS correspondent. 
  "Our position has remained the same as before: We are for 
the 
conference, which should tackle this problem," the high-ranking 
Russian diplomat said. "It should be considered multilaterally, 
since the dialogue on the bilateral level has failed." 
  The Moscow initiative, which was confirmed by Russian 
Federation President Boris Yeltsin at his recent talks with 
President of the Republic of Korea Kim Yong-sam, envisions the 
convening of an international conference on security and 
nuclear-free status of the Korean peninsula, with the 
participation of South and North Korea, Russia, the United 
States, China, and Japan, as well as the United Nations and the 
IAEA (the International Atomic Energy Agency). "We believe that 
this is the way out of the situation," said Aleksandr Panov. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

