<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Fears Koreans To Target Embassy in Pyongyang </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow Fears Koreans To Target Embassy in Pyongyang </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0806082794 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 8 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM0806082794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Aleksandr Platkovskiy report: "Pyongyang Meets Threat With </F>
Threat"] 
  [Text] Consultations are being held in the UN Security 
Council about how best to punish the DPRK for disrupting 
international monitoring of [kontrol nad] its nuclear programs. 
Meanwhile, Pyongyang is threatening to withdraw once and for all 
from the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons. 
  The majority of Security Council members no longer has any 
doubt that the introduction of sanctions against the DPRK is the 
best means of forcing the North Korean leadership to come to its 
senses. However, Moscow views such a development as extremely 
undesirable. 
  Trading interests aside, there is also the Russian Embassy 
in 
the DPRK, which the Ministry of Foreign Affairs fears would 
become the target of the "uncontrollable wrath of the Korean 
people" -- to use Pyongyang's terminology. Our diplomats and 
their families would feel this wrath directly were Russia to 
support any sanctions, whose introduction Pyongyang assesses as 
"a declaration of war." 
  Meanwile, our military experts are already analyzing the 
possible reaction of the North Korean leadership to the 
introduction of sanctions. A military specialist who worked in 
the DPRK for several years told IZVESTIYA that field commanders 
are in a state of constant stress. Especially those whose 
subunits are stationed in the region of the demilitarized zone. 
No one can predict what may prompt a salvo of fire on Seoul 
from the almost 10,000 North Korean guns stationed in this 
extremely dangerous region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

