<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Holds Briefing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Spokesman Holds Briefing </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Comments on NATO Pact </H4>

<F P=102> LD0706180894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1654 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706180894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Yuriy Kozlov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 7 TASS -- The Russian side "is striving 
for deepened partnership with NATO without mutual vetoes and 
surprises,". This is the essence of Russian approach to the 
elaboration of a Russia-NATO program and involvement in the 
Partnership for Peace Program, head of the Russian Foreign 
Ministry's Information and Press Department Grigoriy Karasin 
told a briefing here today. 
  The official commented on the upcoming meeting of foreign 
ministers from the North Atlantic Cooperation Council scheduled 
for June 10 in Istanbul. The Russian delegation will be headed 
by Andrey Kozyrev. 
  Moscow has noted recent statements of representatives of 
several NATO member-states about the readiness to account the 
Russian role in provision of European security and stability, 
said Karasin. 
  Speaking of the North Atlantic Cooperation Council, Karasin 
said that Russia considers this organization to be important and 
useful, whose role in the system of European cooperation 
institutions will increase. In accordance with the Russian 
concept of European partnership, the council is bound to 
coordinate cooperation in the military-political sphere, namely 
peace-making, under the aegis of CSCE, he added. The council 
could also supervise the implementation of NATO's Partnership 
for Peace Program. 
  According to the Foreign Ministry's representative, the 
Istanbul meeting is expected to result in a political statement 
on topical issues of European and world politics. The ministers 
will also discuss and take into account a report on cooperation 
in peace- making prepared by the council's special group. 

</TEXT>

