<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev: Partnership for Peace `No Panacea' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev: Partnership for Peace `No Panacea' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706173094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1517 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706173094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: by correspondents </F>
Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy Trubetskoy, and others] 
  [Text] Russian foreign minister stressed in an interview 
with Interfax that the NATO Partnership for Peace program was no 
panacea for Russia. "We are not stuck on this program," he added. 
  Kozyrev announced that he was going to discuss the issue at 
the meeting of the NATO Cooperation Council (NACC) in Istanbul 
in which he would arrive from Paris. "We believe that the NACC 
is maybe of even more importance than the Partnership for Peace 
program," he pointed out. We do not agree that the role of the 
NACC be brought down to that of a NATO adjunct. The NACC has 
its own future. It lets NATO reorganize itself and launch 
multilateral cooperation. This is quite an independent direction 
making a part of pan-European partnership, Kozyrev said. 
  He also announced that in the near future Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin would put forward Russia's initiatives on 
development of pan-European partnership where the CSCE would 
play the key role. 
  Kozyrev stressed that Moscow regarded the Russia-NATO 
document recently introduced in Brussels by Russian Defense 
Minister Pavel Grachev as much more important than the 
Partnership for Peace program. Kozyrev stated that the Russian 
formula in the political sphere of cooperation would be made 
known in Istanbul. "Afterwards, we will calmly negotiate with 
NATO, sign the frame document they are proposing and reach an 
agreement on our Russia-NATO program which is certainly more 
comprehensive and serious. We take the Partnership for Peace 
program into account. It is not primarily important for us. 
However, it is not least important for either," Kozyrev 
emphasized. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39437 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov110_a_94013" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-110 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin on German Visit, NATO Partnership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin on German Visit, NATO Partnership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706171394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1505 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706171394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Gennadiy Kulbitskiy and </F>
Gennadiy Temnenkov] 
  [Text] Mainz, Germany, June 7 TASS -- "My official German 
visit may be held this year," Russian Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin told a news conference here today. 
  He said they have such plans, but everything depends on 
certain circumstances. The prime minister visited Germany a 
year ago, and all programs the sides agreed on are being 
fulfilled. 
  A priority of the Russian Government is to create a legal 
basis for foreign investments, said Chernomyrdin. Russia is 
closely cooperating with Germany in this sphere. Germany ranks 
first in Russian-European trade and economic turnover. 
  At the same time, there were some changes and drops in 
bilateral relations. In the opinion of the premier, these 
things are temporary, as Russia and Germany have old traditions 
and many German firms have long been known on the Russian market. 
  Russia has changed, and there is plenty of possibilities to 
develop economic cooperation. The prime minister called on 
German businessmen for more active work on the Russian market. 
He said Russia has eliminated many obstacles on the way of 
economic cooperation. 
  Asked about the Russian attitude to NATO's Partnership for 
Peace initiative, Chernomyrdin referred to a recent visit of 
Russian Defence minister Pavel Grachev to the NATO Headquarters 
in Brussels. 
  "We have accepted the NATO proposal to participate in the 
program, and we are ready to cooperate. We are sure we have 
done right. I am convinced European problems cannot be solved 
without Russia, and we will participate in the program 
regardless any opinions about this. We should establish 
absolutely normal, partner relations between Russia and NATO," 
he said. 
  Asked to comment on Russian reports claiming the prime 
minister is writing memoirs and planning to publish them in 
Germany, Chernomyrdin said he writes no memoirs as he has much 
other work to do. 
  In conclusion the prime minister thanked German Federal 
Chancellor Helmut Kohl for assistance to his Mainz visit. 

</TEXT>

