<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Attends Paris OECD Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Attends Paris OECD Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Comments on Ties With West, DPRK </H4>

<F P=102> LD0706144394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1325 
GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0706144394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Dmitriy Chubarov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 7 Jun -- The coming signing of a package of 
agreements with the Organization of Economic Cooperation and 
Development (OECD) will be a "major step on the road to 
implementing a strategy of creating political conditions for an 
equitable partnership between Russia and the leading Western 
powers". This was stated today by Russian Federation Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev before his flight to Paris. The head of 
the foreign policy department flew out to the French capital to 
take part in a special meeting with ministers of the 
member-states of the OECD which unites the most developed 
countries in the world. 
  The ceremony of the signing of a declaration on cooperation 
between the Russian Federation and the OECD and also an 
agreement on the OECD's privileges and immunities in the Russian 
Federation will take place in Paris tomorrow, 8 June. 
  Dwelling in this connection on Russia's relations with 
Europe, the minister announced that at the end of the month a 
big agreement might be signed with the European Union at summit 
level. "Thus," he added, "this summer we will already start to 
reap the economic harvest of our political partnership." 
  At the request of journalists, A. Kozyrev expressed his 
opinion on the "nuclear problem" on the Korean peninsula and the 
calls by some countries for economic sanctions to be introduced 
against the DPRK. "In the final count," he said, "it may come to 
a stage-by- stage introduction of sanctions. But before that 
all the other possibilities should be exhausted, including the 
possibility of holding an international conference." 
  Speaking of Russia's possible participation in the 
"Partnership for Peace" program, the Russian Federation foreign 
minister stressed that this program not regarded by the Russian 
side as a panacea. In Istanbul at the end of the week he is to 
take part in a session of the North Atlantic Cooperation 
Council. "This course of action is in keeping with our strategy 
for European partnership," A. Kozyrev said. He said that in the 
near future the Russian president will make initiatives on this, 
initiatives in which the central role in the coordinating the 
process of integration in Europe is allotted to the CSCE. 

</TEXT>

