<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karasin on Partnership Agreement With European Union </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karasin on Partnership Agreement With European Union </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706224394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1512 
GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0706224394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Yuriy Kozlov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 7 Jun -- The text of the agreement on 
partnership and cooperation between the Russian Federation and 
the European Union is finally agreed and the necessary 
procedures for it to be signed have begun. That is what 
Grigoriy Karasin, head of the Russian Foreign Ministry 
Information and Press Department, told today's briefing for 
Russian and foreign correspondents. He spoke about the results 
of the consultations held in Moscow yesterday. Heads of Foreign 
Ministry political departments from Greece, Belgium, and Germany 
took part in the talks. 
  Karasin said that no effort would be spared to ensure that 
the agreements are signed during the meeting of the European 
Council's heads of states and governments of the European Union, 
which will take place on the Greek island of Kerkira on 24-25 
June 1994. 
  The talks participants, the official spokesman of the 
Russian 
foreign policy department said, also discussed the problem of 
nuclear non-proliferation on the Korean Peninsula. 
Representatives of the European Union, he said, expressed 
concern at tension increasing there because of North Korea's 
unwillingness to achieve a comprehensive settlement. In its 
turn, the Russian side drew attention to the importance of 
working on the idea of convening an international conference 
with the participation of the Russian Federation, the United 
States, China, Japan, North Korea, the Republic of Korea, and 
also representatives of the United Nations, and the IAEA, so 
that it could discuss the problem of security in and a 
non-nuclear status for the Korean Peninsula. 
  During discussion of the situation in the former Yugoslavia, 
Grigoriy Karasin continued, it was noted that there was a 
coincidence of views on and approaches to the situation in 
Bosnia- Herzegovina. It was agreed that that there is a need 
for the Russian Federation, the European Union, and the United 
States to step up efforts with a view to moving closer to a 
political solution. 
  Other topical international problems were also thoroughly 
discussed. Among them were the situation in the Near East and 
the implementation of the Israeli-Palestinian agreement, the 
situation in the Republic of South Africa following the first 
general elections, relations between Russia and the Baltic 
region and Ukraine, and peace-keeping operations in Georgia and 
Nagorno- Karabakh. The representatives of Greece, Belgium, and 
Germany said that the European Union intends to assist in 
developing and strengthening the CIS. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

