<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shokhin Says Cooperation Accord With EU `Virtually Ready' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shokhin Says Cooperation Accord With EU `Virtually Ready' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706141094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1244 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706141094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The agreement on partnership and cooperation between 
Russia and the European Union is "virtually ready to be signed," 
an aide to Russia's Deputy Premier Aleksandr Shokhin told 
INTERFAX on Tuesday. 
  Shokhin is in charge of preparations for signing the 
agreement. 
  As the aide said, the problems, that could hinder the 
signing 
of the agreement during the EU summit to be held on the Greek 
Island of Corfu on June 24-26, have virtually been resolved. 
  Only the insignificant differences with Greece concerning 
privileges for merchant ships remain to be settled. Greece 
wants such privileges to be spread to its ships going under the 
flags of other countries, such as Panama and Liberia. As for 
Russia, it insists that the privileges must be applied only to 
the ships going under their own nation's flag. 
  According to the source, these differences can be viewed as 
"technical issues". He said he is firmly confident that the 
agreement between Russia and the EU will be signed during the 
upcoming EU summit. 
  Earlier, during a visit to Moscow by France's Foreign 
Minister, Alan Juppe, and his talks with Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin, Paris withdrew its reservations concerning 
Russia's trade in nuclear materials. It's common knowledge 
that, like Russia, France is a major supplier of fuel for 
nuclear-power plants in Europe. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

