<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Security Council Challenged Over Iraq Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Security Council Challenged Over Iraq Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706150094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1405 
GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0706150094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 7 Jun (ITAR-TASS) -- Russia is in favor of 
rigidly observing the appropriate resolutions of the UN Security 
Council which have established the regime of trade and economic 
sanctions against Iraq. However, the same resolutions allow 
supplies of goods and produce to Iraq in the form of 
humanitarian aid, provided permission exists from the Security 
Council committee for sanctions, said Grigoriy Karasin, director 
of the information and press department of the Russian 
Federation Foreign Ministry, speaking at a briefing today. 
  In this connection he said that the Russian side is 
seriously 
concerned over a number of Russia's humanitarian requests which 
are now going through the UN Security Council committee for 
sanctions. In particular, for several years now the Committee 
has been blocking Russia's request to supply Iraq with equipment 
in order to continue the construction of Iraq's "Yusufiyah" 
thermal electric power station . 
  "We have always believed that the purpose of our project is 
solely humanitarian. On no account does it contradict the well 
known resolutions of the UN Security Council, particularly 
considering that the special missions of the UN which at one 
time visited Iraq attributed the restoration and the 
construction of the power station in that country to 
humanitarian needs," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

