<H3> <TI>   Soskovets, Malaysian Leaders Comment on MiG-29 Deal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Soskovets, Malaysian Leaders Comment on MiG-29 Deal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706121194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0754 
GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0706121194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Stanislav Bychkov and Oleg </F>
Velichko] 
  [Excerpts] Kuala Lumpur, 7 Jun -- Russia has entered the 
Southeast Asian arms market with the signing here today of a 
contract to supply Malaysia with 18 MiG-29 fighters. [passage 
omitted] 
  It is very important for Malaysia that, by starting 
wide-scale business cooperation with us, Russia is willing to 
hand over advanced technology to the Malaysians, [Deputy 
Malaysian Prime Minister] Anwar bin Ibragim stressed in an 
interview for an ITAR- TASS correspondent. For this reason, he 
said, Kuala Lumpur regards this present deal as a first major 
step in bilateral ties in the development of the industrial 
infrastructure, power engineering, and other spheres. With full 
justification one can call today's event historic, both for 
Malaysia and for Russia, Malaysian Defense Minister Najib Abdul 
Razak told an ITAR-TASS correspondent. "We are the first 
country in the region to begin defense cooperation with Russia, 
cooperation which is destined to open up broad new opportunities 
for business relations between us," the defense minister said. 
  In a speech at the signing ceremony, Oleg Soskovets [first 
deputy prime minister of Russia] pointed out that the contract 
is evidence of the start of a new stage in the development of 
bilateral relations. "The main thing now, from Russia's point 
of view, is to transform the extensive existing potential into a 
stable range of practical ties between the two countries," he 
stressed. 

</TEXT>

