<H3> <TI>   Soskovets on Possible Arms Center in Malaysia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Soskovets on Possible Arms Center in Malaysia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706162994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1232 
GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0706162994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Stanislav Bychkov and Oleg </F>
Velichko] 
  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, 7 Jun -- "Since Malaysia has become 
the first country in Southeast Asia to acquire Russian weapons, 
we discussed the possibility of establishing in this country a 
center for their further promotion in the region." This was 
stated to an ITAR-TASS correspondent by First Vice Premier Oleg 
Soskovets after his meeting today with Malaysian Prime Minister 
Mahathir Mohamad. The Russian Government's representative is in 
Kuala Lumpur on an official visit, and was today present at the 
ceremony of signing the contract for the delivery to Malaysia of 
18 Russian MiG-29 fighters. 
  Malaysia needs new technologies, new scientific 
developments, 
and is displaying a practical interest in the sphere of 
telecommunications and space technology. "They are not 
wondering like some figures have started doing in Russia about 
whether to be in space or not, but they intend to get on with 
it," O. Soskovets said. Thus, during the conversation with the 
head of the Malaysian Cabinet, accord was reached "on 
large-scale and long-term scientific-technical cooperation and 
the transfer of individual Russian technologies to Malaysia." 
It was an "extraordinarily intensive conversation between two 
sides with an interest in cooperation," O. Soskovets stressed. 
  The new Malaysian-Russian relations are "called upon to 
serve 
the two countries for a minimum of 20 years," Malaysian Defense 
Minister Mohamad Najib Abdul Razak stated during today's 
meeting. The sides discussed the prospects for cooperation in 
military technology as a result of signing the contract on the 
MiGs. The war minister called the agreement "the biggest deal 
with Russia," and expressed "interest" in the development and 
expansion of such cooperation. 

</TEXT>

