<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shaposhnikov Denies MiG's Sold Cheaply </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shaposhnikov Denies MiG's Sold Cheaply </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806141594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1329 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The contract for export of 18 Russian MiG-29 
fighters to Malaysia is extremely advantageous for Russia, the 
Russian president's representative in the Rosvooruzheniye state 
concern, Marshal Yevgeniy Shaposhnikov told INTERFAX. 
  "Arms exports are always beneficial, particularly given the 
current state of Russia's arms complex and shortages of hard 
currency," he said. He also noted that the Russian-Malaysian 
contract was the first step towards the introduction of Russian 
weapons and other goods in this region. 
  He denied reports that the MiG fighters had been sold at 
dumping prices. "Simply, part of the MiG fighters' cost will be 
paid by supplies of Malaysian goods, including palm oil," he 
said. 
  He said that before the Rosvooruzheniye concern established 
its absolute control on the arms market, other agencies had 
wanted to sign this contract. So all these accusations came 
from the people who failed to get the deal, he said. 
  The latest contract could be followed by other ones with 
Southeast Asian and other countries, said Shaposhnikov. 
  According to unofficial sources, the contract is estimated 
at 
600 million dollars. Only 20 to 25 percent of the contract will 
be paid in palm oil supplies. 

</TEXT>

