<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton `Very Satisfied' With Relations With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clinton `Very Satisfied' With Relations With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM0706101394 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 7 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM0706101394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Manki Ponomarev report: "Bill Clinton: Russia Is a Great </F>
Power"] 
  [Text] U.S. President Bill Clinton, in Europe to celebrate 
the 50th anniversary of the landing of allied troops in 
Normandy, is being subjected to a concentrated assault by 
representatives of the mass media. They are taking the 
opportunity to interview the head of the White House, to 
ascertain his views on particular topical issues, and to make 
them known to the public. 
  In one such interview which Clinton granted to French 
television, he specially dwelt on relations with Russia and 
declared that he was "very satisfied" with their development. 
In this connection the President emphasized that Russia "really 
is a great power." At the upcoming G-7 meeting in Italy, he 
pointed out, Russia will take part at a "higher level than ever" 
and will participate fully in the discussion of political 
questions. 
  Touching on the problem of the Russian Federation Armed 
Forces' participation in settling conflicts in the former Soviet 
republics, Bill Clinton pointed out that "Russia can play a 
leading role in resolving certain problems in that region." But 
on condition, he remarked, that "the UN and other multilateral 
forces participate" in this process. "Thus it is not a question 
of restoring the empire. Great power -- yes; empire -- no," the 
head of the White House concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

