<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Denies Peacekeeper Deployment in Abkhazia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Denies Peacekeeper Deployment in Abkhazia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706174294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1613 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706174294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A top-ranking official of the Russian Defense 
Ministry has said that reports on the start of the deployment of 
peacekeeping forces in the area of the Georgian-Abkhazian 
conflict on June 7 are not true. 
  The Russian general who spoke on condition of anonymity 
pointed out in an interview with Interfax Tuesday that President 
Yeltsin had given the Defense Ministry no instructions to start 
deploying peacekeepers along the border river Inguri to separate 
the warring sides. 
  The Interfax interviewee emphasized that the ministry was 
not 
entitled to independently make such decisions. At the same 
time, he did not preclude that the peacekeeping operation could 
start in the conflict area within the next few days. 
  With a majority of one vote, the Federation Council declined 
Yeltsin's request to send a 1,500-strong Russian contingent to 
the conflict area last week. The deputies decided that the 
Russian troops' legal status had not been worked through as 
thoroughly as it should have been done. 
  Moscow did not preclude that the Federation Council would 
return to considering the Russian peacekeepers' deployment along 
the Inguri at its regular session on June 21. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

