<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yarov Describes Visit to India as `Successful' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yarov Describes Visit to India as `Successful' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706153294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1343 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Bulantsev] </F>
  [Text] New Delhi June 7 TASS -- "Our delegation's visit to 
India was successful. In the course of our negotiations with 
the Indian leaders we were able to work out a mechanism for 
achieving mutual understanding between our young Russia and the 
renovated India, and for achieving mutually acceptable 
decisions," Vice- Chairman of the Russian Government Yuriy Yarov 
told a press conference here today. He is currently visiting 
the Indian capital at the head of a high-ranking Russian 
delegation. 
  "As a result of the scrupulous work done by the two sides," 
Yarov said, "we were able to draw up a package of documents that 
are expected to be concluded at the end of Prime Minister 
Narasimha Rao's official visit to Russia at the end of June and 
the beginning of July. The agreements are practically ready to 
be signed and they cover many areas of cooperation, including 
the protection of investments, development of tourism, business 
partnership in science and technology, implementation of joint 
ecological projects and measures to protect the environment, etc. 
  Yarov did not dodge some sharp questions put to him by 
journalists about the Russo-Indian relations. He stated, for 
instance, that the results of bilateral contacts over the past 
two years were unsatisfactory. "At the present time, the trade 
turnover between our two countries amounts to 25 billion rupees 
(about 782 million U.S. dollars), which is absolutely 
insufficient. This sum has to be at least doubled by the end of 
the year," Yarov stated. 
  Asked about the irregularity of Russian deliveries of spare 
parts to the Indian armed forces, the head of the Russian 
delegation said that this was a "feeble link" in Russo-Indian 
cooperation. 
  However, on the whole, Yarov sounded quite optimistic. Asked 
by ITAR-TASS to sum up the results of the Russian delegation's 
work in India, he said: "We were able to do a lot during this 
brief period, but there is still much work ahead. On the whole, 
we are satisfied with our results. Our relations with India 
were made more dynamic. We want to be friends with India and we 
shall do our best to promote this friendship." 
  Yarov said that agreement was reached on Premier Viktor 
Chernomyrdin's visit to India, which will take place in the near 
future. 
  Yarov will be received by Indian Prime Minister Narasimha 
Rao 
today, after which the Russian delegation will leave for home. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

