<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chechen Oppositin Considers `Coercive Methods' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chechen Oppositin Considers `Coercive Methods' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706173594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1356 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706173594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Chechen opposition, which understands that 
Chechnya's leadership will not voluntarily refuse from power, 
does not rule out that coercive methods can be used to solve the 
conflict, the headquarters of the opposition situated in the 
republic's Nadterechny region reported to Interfax Tuesday. 
They made it clear that the political forces opposing President 
Dzhokhar Dudayev would resort to coercive measures only in case 
that the official formations in Groznyy are the first to use 
arms. 
  A representative of the headquarters who preferred to stay 
anonymous declared that last Sunday the opposition manage to 
conduct its congress in the regional center of Znamenskoe. As 
many as 2500 delegates were present at the congress. 
  However, as Groznyy reports, the opposition's congress was 
disrupted because the majority of those invited to the congress 
boycotted it. 
  Meanwhile, the congress' delegate Ruslan Martagov told our 
Interfax correspondent that the congress took place despite a 
tough confrontation on the part of Groznyy. 
  In his words, the congress urged that Chechen President 
Dzhokhar Dudayev and Vice President Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev should 
immediately resign and the republic's parliament should pass a 
decision on democratic elections. According to the opposition, 
this decision should be adopted before June 15 and then the 
parliament should announce about its self-disbandment. 
  As the opposition believes, new elections should be held not 
later than August 1994. The authorities should release all 
political prisoners and transfer all authorities to the 
Temporary Council of the Chechen Republic being created by the 
opposition. 
  The resolution adopted by the congress underlines that the 
Temporary Council created in winter 1994 takes all the functions 
of the representative power until the time of the new elections. 

</TEXT>

