<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Komi Leader Affirms Role in Federation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Komi Leader Affirms Role in Federation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0706134594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1032 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0706134594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia must have only one president, said Yuriy 
Spiridonov, the recently elected head of the Komi Republic. He 
told Interfax in an exclusive interview on the eve of the 
inauguration ceremony that the Komi leaders had turned down the 
idea of instituting the post of president in their republic. 
"We are an inalienable part of the Russian Federation," he 
said. "Even if the leaders of the republics and regions are 
elected by the people, they must not be called presidents, he 
added. 
  To quote Spiridonov, the Constitution of the Komi Republic 
provides the local parliament with sufficient rights to control 
the head of the government. "A president does not head either 
the legislative or the executive bodies. He is above both, so 
it is not the president that we are electing. The head of the 
Komi Republic directly runs the government, the responsibility 
he bears is much greater than that of the president of any 
republic," he said. 
  He expressed regret that the new Russian Constitution does 
not contain the Federation Treaty. This makes the Center and 
the constituent entities conclude a bilateral agreement in each 
particular instance, said Spiridonov. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

