<H3> <TI>   DPRK Foreign Minister Visits </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Foreign Minister Visits </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Meets With Kravchuk </H4>

<F P=102> LD0706172194 Kiev UT-1 Television Network in Ukrainian 1600 
GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0706172194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UT-1 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk today received 
DPRK Foreign Minister Kim Yong-nam. 
  [Unidentified correspondent] The Ukrainian president warmly 
greeted the DPRK's delegation led by Foreign Minister Kim 
Yong-nam. The DPRK was one of the world's first countries to 
recognize Ukraine's independence and to establish diplomatic 
relations with it. 
  During a conversation, Leonid Kravchuk informed the Korean 
guests of the present situation in Ukraine and stressed that it 
is stable. Out state's president noted that political battles 
are being fought in Ukraine, but added that there is no acute 
confrontation. On the issue of Crimea, Leonid Kravchuk 
reiterated it is being settled within the framework of 
constitutional methods. 
  The Korean side expressed interest in developing cooperation 
with Ukraine. Issues of mutual interest to both states were 
discussed. Ukrainian Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko took part 
in the conversation. 
  The DPRK delegation, led by Foreign Minister Kim Yong-nam, 
was today also received by Oleksandr Tkachenko, first deputy 
chairman of the Ukrainian Supreme Council, who told the guests 
about the activity of Ukraine's new democratically elected 
parliament. The quests were acquainted with the specialist work 
being carried out by the Ukrainian Parliament, which is 
fatefully entrusted with resolving many problems in order to 
pull the economy out of a crisis, and improve the social 
security of Ukraine's population at a hard time of market 
reforms. 
  I note that agreements on trade, economic, and scientific 
and 
technological cooperation were concluded between Ukraine and the 
DPRK last year. The Korean side today takes interest in signing 
such interstate documents as a treaty on friendship and 
cooperation, agreements on cultural relations, legal assistance, 
and other documents which would promote bilateral ties. 
  Anatoliy Zlenko and Borys Oliynyk, chairman of the Ukrainian 
Supreme Council Foreign affairs and CIS Relations Commission, 
took part in the conversation. 

</TEXT>

