<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Labor Ministry Reports Unemployment Increases in 1994 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Labor Ministry Reports Unemployment Increases in 1994 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS0806071794 Kiev UKRINFORM in English 0529 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0806071794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UKRINFORM </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Business News Weekly" feature, 30 May-5 Jun 94] </F>
  [Text] According to the Ukrainian Labor Ministry, 
Ukrainian employment centers registered 236,800 jobless persons 
in the first quarter of 1994. 123,400 of these were registered 
back in 1993. 
  However, hidden unemployment increased at industrial 
enterprises, particularly those under the Ministry of 
engineering, MIC [Military Industrial Complex] and conversion. 
  As tentative estimates by the Labor Ministry suggest, about 
2,200,000 workers were on unpaid leaves in the first quarter, or 
14.2 per cent of the total number of workforce. March's 
official unemployment rate was stated at 0.35 per cent. 
  However, as independent experts' data, which were made 
public 
at the International Conference on Economics in Kiev in late 
May, suggest, Ukraine's hidden unemployment minimal rate is in 
excess of 7 million workers. Meanwhile, some 120,000 jobs 
remain vacant. 
  The State's employment bodies and local authorities are 
reported as intending to step up implementation of the national 
and territorial employment programs, which involve, in 
particular, creation of new jobs at enterprises of all 
proprietorial forms. However, no one can tell how many of these 
or how soon they will be created, except 279,100 jobs reserved 
for citizens certified as unable to compete on par with others 
on Ukraine's labor market. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

