<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Communication Problems Caused Interception </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Communication Problems Caused Interception </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806133194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1323 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806133194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Irina Shchegoleva] </F>
  [Text] Sochi June 8 TASS -- The severance of ties and 
communication between the republics of the former Soviet Union 
caused Tuesday's incident involving an American plane, according 
to a duty officer of Sochi's airport. 
  The plane en route to Tbilisi and Baku to deliver supplies 
for American diplomats in Georgia and Azerbaijan violated 
Russia's airspace and was landed at Sochi's Adler airport at 
14:37 on Tuesday. Three hours later, at 17:46, when the 
incident was settled the plane continued the flight. 
  "Before we had direct telephone lines with all nearest 
district centres and such an incident could have been settled 
much faster," Vyacheslav Isayev, duty officer of Sochi's 
airport, said. 
  "There are no flights from Adler to Sukhumi (capital of 
Abkhazia) -- neither civil nor military. There is no 
communication. It is extremely hard to work in such 
conditions," he said. 

</TEXT>

