<H3> <TI>   Reportage on CIS Interparliamentary Session </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on CIS Interparliamentary Session </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Peacekeeping Discussed </H4>

<F P=102> LD0806130794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1230 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806130794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Viktor Shulman] </F>
  [Text] St. Petersburg June 8 TASS -- "Peace is still too 
fragile and demands for the maximum results in the settlement of 
the six-year armed conflict are hardly acceptable," Russian 
Ambassador at Large Vladimir Kazimirov, who has been acting as 
the Russian president's special envoy to Karabakh, said at the 
session of the CIS inter-parliamentary assembly. He was 
speaking in the discussion of the Commonwealth's peace-keeping 
missions. 
  Kazimirov spoke after chairman of Kyrgyzstan's parliament 
Medetkan Sherimkulov reported on the work done by the CIS 
interparliamentary group led by him to promote the peaceful 
settlement in Nagorno-Karabakh. 
  Sherimkulov said in his report that since a cease-fire 
protocol was signed in Bishkek, the warring parties have 
observed its provisions in the zone of the Armenian-Azeri 
conflict in the past four weeks. 

</TEXT>

