<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Prime Minister on Cabinet's Priorities </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputy Prime Minister on Cabinet's Priorities </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806211094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1805 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806211094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Moldovan Vice-Premier Ion Gutu told a news 
conference in Kishinev [Chisinau] on Wednesday [8 June] that in 
1994 through 1997 the priorities of the new cabinet will be the 
strengthening of the economy, reforms, social security and the 
expansion of foreign trade. He also said that the government 
program of action will be discussed by parliamentary committees 
and then by a plenary session of parliament. 
  Gutu said the country has made certain financial 
achievements: in May the inflation rate was only 4 percent. 
  Falling production remains the main problem. In the first 
five months industrial production amounted to 71 percent of last 
year's level. The number of employed in industry dropped by a 
third. Many factories are sending their workers on unpaid leave. 
  Gutu said the government wants to suggest to parliament 
making urban land an article of trade, which in his opinion 
could attract foreign investments in the Moldovan economy. 

</TEXT>

