<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-111 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Draft Treaty Calls for $115 Million Payment From Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Draft Treaty Calls for $115 Million Payment From Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806163194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1515 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia may pay as much as $115 million annually to 
Kazakhstan for using the Baykonur space launching center under a 
draft treaty which Kazakh officials submitted to Russian 
negotiators. 
  Kazakh National Space Agency Director Aisultan Kalybayev 
told 
INTERFAX that the draft complied with the agreement that had 
been signed by Presidents Boris Yeltsin and Nursultan Nazarbayev 
on 28 March. 
  In particular, the launching pads and the buildings in the 
town of Leninsk will be rented by Russia for a term of 20 years, 
which may be extended for 10 more years. 
  Kazakhstan had earlier intended to have the rent increased. 
  Kalybayev also said that the electricity and water supply 
bills would be paid separately as would be those for temporary 
seizure of land area where parts of booster rockets might fall. 
The energy rates, he said, will not be higher than those paid 
by Kazakh consumers. 
  Kalybayev said the draft, which he had submitted to his 
Russian counterpart Yuri Koptev, will be finalized in Almaty. 
Koptev is also deputy chairman of the bilateral commission on 
Baykonur. 
  Kalybayev expressed the hope that officials from the two 
countries would meet no later than in mid-June. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

