<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Commander: Border Situation `Extremely Complex' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Commander: Border Situation `Extremely Complex' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906094494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0843 
GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0906094494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Gridneva] </F>
  [Excerpts] Dushanbe, 9 June -- The commander of Russian 
border troops in Tajikistan, Lieutenant General Anatoliy 
Chechulin, has described the operational situation on a wide 
section of the Tajik-Afghan border as extremely complex. He 
said the situation had deteriorated seriously during the last 
few days. The general was speaking at a hurriedly summoned news 
conference to discuss the latest major provocation against 
Russian border guards in the zone patrolled by the Moskovskiy 
border detachment. [passage omitted] 
  These provocations, Anatoliy Chechulin stressed, are not the 
best prelude for the second round of inter-Tajik talks 
provisionally scheduled for 17 June in Tehran. The Russian 
general pinned the blame for the continued provocations both on 
the extremist wing of the Tajik opposition and on the civilian 
and military authorities in certain Afghan border districts, who 
pay lip service to stabilization of the Afghan border situation 
but, at the same time, directly facilitate the staging of these 
provocations. He declared that the most decisive measures would 
be taken against "the instigators and organizers of aggression," 
whom the general held entirely responsible for the possible 
consequences. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

