<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Talks With Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comments on Talks With Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0806210794 Yerevan Armenia's Radio First Program Network 
in Armenian 1900 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0806210794 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan Armenia's Radio First Program Network 
in Armenian 1900 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Armenian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrosyan today 
received Russian Defense Minister and Army General Pavel Grachev 
and the delegation accompanying him. 
  The question of granting the status of a military base to 
the 
Russian Federation Army units stationed in Armenia, the 
prospects of implementing the current plan for the peaceful 
settlement of the Karabakh problem, matters pertaining to the 
organization of Armenia's air defenses, and a number of other 
issues were discussed during the meeting. 
  State Minister Vazgen Sargisyan, Defense Minister Serzh 
Sargisyan, and Interior Minister Vano Siradegyan participated in 
the meeting. 
  Russian Defense Minister and Army General Pavel Grachev 
granted an interview to an ARMENPRES correspondent. Replying to 
a question on the purpose of his visit, he said that he is 
visiting Armenia at the invitation of Armenian President Levon 
Ter-Petrosyan to conduct talks on a number of military-political 
matters, particularly on cooperation between the two countries 
within the framework of the collective security agreement. The 
minister said that the [word indistinct] conditions for the 
deployment of the Russian Army units in the Republic will be 
discussed. Grachev added that matters relating to the 
Karabakh-Azerbaijani conflict will also be discussed during his 
visit to Armenia and meetings with the Republic's leadership. 
In this connection, he specifically emphasized that Armenia and 
Karabakh have signed the agreement on peaceful settlement of the 
conflict worked out with Russian mediation, whereas Azerbaijan 
has so far refrained from doing so. Therefore, after his visit 
to Georgia on Saturday he will go to Baku to meet Aliyev to 
propose that Azerbaijan finally sign the agreement. 
  Commenting on whether the number of Russian troops could be 
increased in Armenia, Grachev noted that there could only be 
talk of reducing them. 
  After his meeting with Armenian President Levon 
Ter-Petrosyan, Mr. Grachev told reporters that he is satisfied 
with the results of his talks with the Armenian president. The 
president and the Armenian people desire to have Russian bases 
on Armenian territory within the framework of the collective 
security agreement and on a bilateral basis to jointly ensure 
the security of Armenia and Russia. The Armenian president 
reiterated support for the implementation of that agreement [on 
Nagorno-Karabakh], which we formulated in Moscow, said the 
Russian defense minister. He added that he will leave for Baku 
on 11 June with these impressions and will ask Aliyev to once 
more reassess the situation and sign the agreement. He 
expressed the hope that after that a real and stable peace will 
be established in Nagorno-Karabakh. 

</TEXT>

