<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meets With Ter-Petrosyan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meets With Ter-Petrosyan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806185794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1650 
GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0806185794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondents Tigran Liloyan and </F>
Mikhail Shevtsov] 
  [Text] Yerevan, 8 Jun -- Russian Defense Minister Pavel 
Grachev, who arrived in Yerevan today, met Armenia's President 
Levon Ter-Petrosyan this evening. He received the consent of 
the head of this state to the establishment of Russian military 
bases on Armenia's territory. 
  Pavel Grachev said that the final calculation of the number 
and armaments of Russian troops in Armenia will be agreed upon 
at by experts tomorrow. The Russian minister said that an 
agreement on Russian military bases in Armenia will in all 
probability be signed by 1 September of this year. He said 
that, as is intended, the motorized rifle division in Gyumri and 
the morotized rifle regiment in Yerevan will remain in Armenia. 
The general made it clear that it is intended to supply more 
equipment to the Russian troops with more to make them mobile in 
the air. 
  Levon Ter-Petrosyan agreed that within the framework of 
ensuring CIS collective security, it is necessary to set up an 
air defense system on Armenia's territory. Touching on the 
agreement on a cease-fire and the disengagement of troops in the 
zone of the Armenian-Azerbaijani conflict, Pavel Grachev said 
that Armenia's president confirmed his readiness to keep to the 
accords reached. 
  Tomorrow, the Russian military delegation will continue its 
work in Armenia, will visit Russian military facilities, and 
will fly to Tbilisi in the evening. 

</TEXT>

