<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin: Russian Troops May Be Withdrawn by 31 Aug </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin: Russian Troops May Be Withdrawn by 31 Aug </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806144494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1329 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806144494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Estonian-Russian talks on troop withdrawal will 
be continued in Moscow "maybe even next week," Russian Deputy 
Foreign Minister Vitaliy Churkin announced in Tallinn today. 
  Commenting on the results of his two-day meetings with 
Estonian Foreign Ministry Vice Chancellor Raul Malk, Churkin 
hoped that the parties would agree that social guarantees be 
given to retired Russian servicemen living in Estonia. Churkin 
said there must be a special document for preventing possible 
tension between Tallinn and Moscow. The document must be 
realistic and conform with the highest standards in human 
rights, Churkin pointed out. 
  Churkin did not rule out that Russian troops could be 
withdrawn from Estonia by August 31, 1994. 
  Russia conditions the troop withdrawal with social 
guarantees 
for retired Russian servicemen in Estonia (there are about 
11,000 of them). There are currently about 2,300 acting Russian 
servicemen in Estonia. 
  Commenting on the recent statement by Estonian Defense Force 
Commander Aleksander Einseln saying that if the appropriate 
order were received, force might be used to push out Russian 
servicemen who would remain in Estonia after August 31, Churkin 
said, "We have absolutely no doubt that the position of Estonia 
consists in settlement of all problems by political means, 
through negotiations. The position of Russia is the same." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-39550 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov111_t_94002" </HT>


