<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Calls Deadline Not `Unrealistic' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Calls Deadline Not `Unrealistic' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806135794 Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network in Estonian 1300 
GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0806135794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network </F>
<F P=105>  Estonian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy Churkin, who 
left Tallinn at lunchtime today, stated at a briefing he gave at 
the airport that, if the will is there, 31 August is not at all 
an unrealistic deadline for the withdrawal of Russian troops. 
According to Churkin, a firm basis by way of a firm agreement is 
required, however, to (?resolve) issues in such an energetic 
manner. According to Churkin, a realistic agreement on Russian 
military pensioners must be concluded so as to eliminate 
tensions in Estonian-Russian relations. 
  During his two-day visit to Tallinn the Russian deputy 
foreign minister continued talks begun in Geneva with Raul Malk, 
the deputy chancellor of the Estonian Foreign Ministry, on 
Saturday [4 June]. Churkin also met with Estonian Prime Minister 
Mart Laar, Foreign Minister Juri Luik, and President Lennart 
Meri. 

</TEXT>

