<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Comments on Einseln Remarks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Comments on Einseln Remarks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806122794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1140 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806122794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Albert Maloveryan] </F>
  [Text] Tallinn June 8 TASS -- Commenting on the recent 
statement by the commander of the Estonian defence forces, 
General Einseln, on the readiness of the troops loyal to him to 
use force, if ordered, in the event of Russia's failure to 
withdraw its troops by August 31, spokesman for the Russian 
Ministry of Foreign Affairs Vitaliy Churkin said today that his 
country judged about Estonia's position by "responsible 
statements of responsible officials" and was sure that Estonia, 
just as Russia, favoured political solutions to all problems. 
  Churkin was speaking after a two-day meeting with his 
Estonian counterpart Raul Malk, which was held in pursuance of 
the accord reached during Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev's recent meeting in Tallinn with Estonian President 
Lennart Meri. 
  Churkin said the problem of the Russian military pensioners 
residing in Estonia remained in the centre of negotiations 
between Estonia and Russia, and expressed the hope that "a new 
page, and probably even a new chapter" will open in 
Russian-Estonian relations thanks to this and other forthcoming 
contacts. 
  Churkin said his talks in Tallinn centered around the 
withdrawal of Russian troops and the dismantling of Russian 
atomic reactors in the training centre for Russian submarine 
power plant operators in Paldiski. Churkin expressed confidence 
that the sides would reach an agreement which would be 
"realistic and rule out any tension in relations between the two 
countries". 
  As concerns the Russian military pensioners residing in the 
republic, Churkin expressed the confidence that the agreement on 
their fate will "also be realistic and meet the world's highest 
standards in the field of human rights". 

</TEXT>

