<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zyuganov Does Not Rule Out Early Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zyuganov Does Not Rule Out Early Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806164194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1459 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806164194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Speaking at a news conference in Moscow today, 
leader of the communists in the Russian State Duma Gennadiy 
Zyuganov did not rule out the possibility that in 
September-October 1994 the authorities will launch what he 
called another blitzkrieg: presidential elections. 
  Speaking of his recent tour of the Volga region and Russia's 
far north he said he had seen a sharp economic decline and a 
sharp rise in crime. He said that if this trend continues, the 
introduction of extraordinary measures by any government is 
inevitable within the next few months. 
  Zyuganov also spoke of what he called favorable symptoms: 
All the regions he visited have swung to the political left and 
the position of the Communist Party has strengthened greatly. 
He said that what is called the democratic government has no 
prestige in these regions. 
  He said that the best next move before the introduction of a 
state of emergency would be that suggested by the Accord for 
Russia movement: To work out a common opposition program, 
propose a team capable of carrying it out, unite political 
efforts and win over industrial circles and trade unions. 

</TEXT>

