<H3> <TI>   Ex-Zhirinovskiy Followers Form Parliamentary Group </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ex-Zhirinovskiy Followers Form Parliamentary Group </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0806154094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1457 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0806154094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Alexandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 8 TASS -- Six defectors from 
Zhirinovskiy's faction in the Russian State Duma have announced 
the creation of their own parliamentary group called "Derzhava" 
(Great Power). 
  The ex-Zhirinovtsi, who earlier voiced their intentions to 
join far liberal "Union of December 12" faction, this time 
declared that they would contribute to the realisation of the 
idea to set up the nation-wide patriotic "Derzhava" movement 
proclaimed recently by former Vice-President Aleksandr Rutskoy. 
  Rutskoy's camp seems to be not happy with such allies. 
Chairman of Rutskoy's Russian Social-Democratic People's Party 
[RSDPP] Vasiliy Lipitskiy told TASS today that the statement of 
Zhirinovskiy's defectors "is in no way in line with the 
interests and objectives of the RSDPP". He said that they have 
made "a false step" by using the name "Derzhava" for their own 
purposes. 
  "I really doubt whether the deputies who have not yet 
displayed any solid principles would be able to represent 
interests of any public movement", Lipitskiy said. 
  According to the State Duma's regulations, a new 
parliamentary group needs to enlist at least 35 MPs to be 
officially registered. 

</TEXT>

